In this paper we present new archaeological data that increases our knowledge about dogs (Canis familiaris) in prehispanic times. 
especially in terms of their general morphology and the number of breeds that existed in central Mesoamerica. A collection of 27 
dogsfmm burials dating to the earliest occupation at Tula, Hidalgo (ca. 650-750 A.D.) is examined. The results show the pres­
ence of three well-defined breeds. This discovery establishes the existence of several different 

breeds of dogs in ancient Mesoamer­ica and provides criteria for describing the general physical characteristic.1· of each type. The three kinds of canines recognized in this study include (I) a medium-size dog with hai1; (2) another with similar dimensions hut hairless, and ( 3) a smaller breed with hair (about 30 percent smaller than the medium-sized examples). These three types fit Bernardino de Sahagun ',1· descriptions of dogs from the central Mexican highlands in the sixteenth century. Our research allows us to establish the presence of these ani­mals in this region beginning in the seventh century A.D. The three breeds include the common Mesoamerican dog or itzcuintli, the hairless dog or xoloitzcuintli and the smaller dog or tlalchichi. Additionally, the establishment of three separate breeds addresses debates in the literature concerning the nature of prehispanic canines. 
